{"entries":[{"stem":"fourier-transform-v1","path":"contracts/fourier-transform-v1.yaml","description":"Discrete Fourier Transform — DFT, FFT (Cooley-Tukey), inverse DFT. Covers the spectral analysis chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["dft","fft","inverse_dft","parseval"],"obligation_types":["equivalence","equivalence","invariant"],"properties":["FFT equals DFT","IDFT round-trip","Parseval energy conservation"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 8 Spectral Methods","Cooley & Tukey (1965) An Algorithm for the Machine Calculation of Complex Fourier Series"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"fourier-transform-v1 Discrete Fourier Transform — DFT, FFT (Cooley-Tukey), inverse DFT. Covers the spectral analysis chapter of nlib.\n dft X_k = sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x_n * exp(-2*pi*i*k*n / N) for k = 0..N-1 DFT is a unitary transform (up to scaling by sqrt(N)) fft Cooley-Tukey radix-2 decimation-in-time:\nX_k = E_k + W_N^k * O_k  for k = 0..N/2-1\nX_{k+N/2} = E_k - W_N^k * O_k\nwhere E = FFT(x_even), O = FFT(x_odd), W_N = exp(-2*pi*i/N)\n O(N log N) operations vs O(N^2) for DFT Numerically equivalent to DFT inverse_dft x_n = (1/N) * sum_{k=0}^{N-1} X_k * exp(2*pi*i*k*n / N) idft is the exact inverse of dft parseval sum |x_n|^2 = (1/N) * sum |X_k|^2 FFT equals DFT |fft(x) - dft(x)| < 1e-10 for all x of length 2^m IDFT round-trip |idft(dft(x)) - x| < 1e-10 Parseval energy conservation sum|x|^2 == (1/N)*sum|X|^2 within tolerance Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 8 Spectral Methods Cooley & Tukey (1965) An Algorithm for the Machine Calculation of Complex Fourier Series"},{"stem":"graph-algorithms-v1","path":"contracts/graph-algorithms-v1.yaml","description":"Graph algorithms — Dijkstra shortest path, Kruskal MST, BFS, DFS. Covers the graph theory chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["bfs","dfs","dijkstra","kruskal_mst"],"obligation_types":["postcondition","postcondition","postcondition","invariant"],"properties":["Dijkstra shortest path optimality","Kruskal MST minimality","BFS level correctness","MST edge count"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 11 Graphs","Cormen et al. (2009) Introduction to Algorithms, 3rd Ed. — Part VI Graph Algorithms"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"graph-algorithms-v1 Graph algorithms — Dijkstra shortest path, Kruskal MST, BFS, DFS. Covers the graph theory chapter of nlib.\n bfs Queue Q; mark s visited; enqueue s\nwhile Q not empty:\n  u = dequeue(Q)\n  for each neighbor v of u:\n    if v not visited: mark v; enqueue v; level[v] = level[u] + 1\n Visits vertices in non-decreasing level order dfs Stack S (or recursion); push s\nwhile S not empty:\n  u = pop(S)\n  if u not visited: mark u visited\n    for each neighbor v of u: push v\n Explores depth-first: children before siblings dijkstra dist[s] = 0; dist[v] = infinity for v != s\nwhile Q not empty:\n  u = extract_min(Q)\n  for each neighbor v of u:\n    if dist[u] + w(u,v) < dist[v]:\n      dist[v] = dist[u] + w(u,v)\n      prev[v] = u\n Triangle inequality: dist[v] <= dist[u] + w(u,v) Once extracted from Q, dist[u] is final kruskal_mst Sort edges by weight ascending.\nFor each edge (u, v, w) in sorted order:\n  if find(u) != find(v):\n    union(u, v); add (u,v,w) to MST\n Cut property: lightest crossing edge is in MST Dijkstra shortest path optimality dist[v] == shortest_path_weight(s, v) for all reachable v Kruskal MST minimality weight(MST) <= weight(T) for all spanning trees T BFS level correctness level[v] == min hops from s to v MST edge count |MST.edges| == |V| - 1 Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 11 Graphs Cormen et al. (2009) Introduction to Algorithms, 3rd Ed. — Part VI Graph Algorithms"},{"stem":"integration-v1","path":"contracts/integration-v1.yaml","description":"Numerical quadrature — trapezoid rule, Simpson's rule, adaptive quadrature. Covers the numerical integration chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["adaptive_quadrature","simpson","trapezoid"],"obligation_types":["postcondition","postcondition","invariant","bound"],"properties":["Trapezoid exact for linear functions","Simpson exact for cubics","Adaptive convergence","Trapezoid error order"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 7 Integration","Davis & Rabinowitz (1984) Methods of Numerical Integration, 2nd Ed."],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"integration-v1 Numerical quadrature — trapezoid rule, Simpson's rule, adaptive quadrature. Covers the numerical integration chapter of nlib.\n adaptive_quadrature Q(a,b) = simpson(a,b,2);  Q2 = simpson(a,b,4)\nif |Q2 - Q| < 15*tol: return Q2 + (Q2 - Q)/15\nelse: return Q(a, mid, tol/2) + Q(mid, b, tol/2)\n Subdivides only where error is large Total subintervals bounded by max_depth simpson I = h/3 * [f(a) + 4*sum_{odd} f(a + i*h) + 2*sum_{even} f(a + i*h) + f(b)]\nwhere h = (b - a) / n, n even\n Exact for polynomials up to degree 3 More accurate than trapezoid for same n trapezoid I = h/2 * [f(a) + 2*sum_{i=1}^{n-1} f(a + i*h) + f(b)]\nwhere h = (b - a) / n\n Exact for linear functions Converges as n -> infinity for continuous f Trapezoid exact for linear functions trapezoid(a*x+b, lo, hi, n) == exact for all n >= 1 Simpson exact for cubics simpson(a*x^3+b*x^2+c*x+d, lo, hi, n) == exact for all even n >= 2 Adaptive convergence |adaptive(f, a, b, tol) - exact| < tol Trapezoid error order |trap(n) - exact| / |trap(n/2) - exact| -> 0.25 as n -> inf Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 7 Integration Davis & Rabinowitz (1984) Methods of Numerical Integration, 2nd Ed."},{"stem":"matrix-algebra-v1","path":"contracts/matrix-algebra-v1.yaml","description":"Dense matrix algebra — matmul, transpose, inverse, Cholesky, determinant. Covers the linear-algebra chapter of nlib with exact formulas.\n","equations":["cholesky","determinant","inverse","matmul","transpose"],"obligation_types":["invariant","equivalence","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Matmul dimension and correctness","Inverse round-trip","Cholesky decomposition round-trip","Determinant multiplicativity"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 4 Linear Algebra","Golub & Van Loan (2013) Matrix Computations, 4th Ed."],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"matrix-algebra-v1 Dense matrix algebra — matmul, transpose, inverse, Cholesky, determinant. Covers the linear-algebra chapter of nlib with exact formulas.\n cholesky A = L * L^T where L is lower-triangular determinant det(A) = sum_{sigma in S_n} sgn(sigma) * prod_{i} A[i, sigma(i)] inverse A * A^{-1} = I_n matmul C[i,j] = sum_{k=0}^{p-1} A[i,k] * B[k,j] Associative: (AB)C == A(BC) within tolerance Distributive: A(B+C) == AB + AC within tolerance transpose A^T[i,j] = A[j,i] Double transpose is identity Matmul dimension and correctness forall A(m,p), B(p,n): matmul(A,B).shape == (m,n) && |C - ref| < eps Inverse round-trip |A * inverse(A) - I| < 1e-8 Cholesky decomposition round-trip |L * L^T - A| < 1e-10 for SPD A Determinant multiplicativity |det(AB) - det(A)*det(B)| < eps Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 4 Linear Algebra Golub & Van Loan (2013) Matrix Computations, 4th Ed."},{"stem":"monte-carlo-v1","path":"contracts/monte-carlo-v1.yaml","description":"Monte Carlo methods — MC integration, bootstrap error estimation, Metropolis-Hastings sampling. Covers the simulation chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["bootstrap_error","mc_integrate","metropolis"],"obligation_types":["invariant","postcondition","invariant","bound"],"properties":["MC integration convergence rate","Bootstrap standard error non-negative","Metropolis detailed balance","MC unbiased estimate"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 10 Monte Carlo","Robert & Casella (2004) Monte Carlo Statistical Methods, 2nd Ed."],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"monte-carlo-v1 Monte Carlo methods — MC integration, bootstrap error estimation, Metropolis-Hastings sampling. Covers the simulation chapter of nlib.\n bootstrap_error For B bootstrap resamples of size N from data:\ntheta_b = statistic(resample_b) for b = 1..B\nse = sqrt(sum (theta_b - mean(theta))^2 / (B - 1))\n se converges to true SE as B -> infinity mc_integrate I approx (b - a) / N * sum_{i=1}^{N} f(x_i) where x_i ~ Uniform(a, b) Variance = (b-a)^2 * Var(f) / N Error decreases as O(1 / sqrt(N)) metropolis Propose x' = x_n + delta where delta ~ proposal_dist\nalpha = min(1, p(x') / p(x_n))\nAccept x_{n+1} = x' with probability alpha, else x_{n+1} = x_n\n Detailed balance: p(x)*T(x->y) = p(y)*T(y->x) Acceptance ratio in (0, 1) for good mixing MC integration convergence rate Var(I_N) = O(1/N) Bootstrap standard error non-negative bootstrap_error(data, stat, B) >= 0.0 Metropolis detailed balance p(x)*T(x,y) == p(y)*T(y,x) MC unbiased estimate E[I_N] == integral(f, a, b) Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 10 Monte Carlo Robert & Casella (2004) Monte Carlo Statistical Methods, 2nd Ed."},{"stem":"nonlinear-solvers-v1","path":"contracts/nonlinear-solvers-v1.yaml","description":"Root-finding algorithms — bisection, Newton-Raphson, secant, fixed-point iteration. Covers the nonlinear solver chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["bisection","fixed_point","newton","secant"],"obligation_types":["postcondition","postcondition","invariant","postcondition"],"properties":["Bisection finds root within tolerance","Newton converges to root","Bisection interval halving","Secant method finds root"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 5 Solvers","Burden & Faires (2015) Numerical Analysis, 10th Ed."],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"nonlinear-solvers-v1 Root-finding algorithms — bisection, Newton-Raphson, secant, fixed-point iteration. Covers the nonlinear solver chapter of nlib.\n bisection Given f continuous on [a,b] with f(a)*f(b) < 0:\nc = (a + b) / 2; if f(a)*f(c) < 0 then b = c else a = c;\nrepeat until |b - a| < tolerance\n Interval halves each iteration: width_n = (b-a) / 2^n fixed_point x_{n+1} = g(x_n) where g(x) = x - f(x)/c for some constant c Linear convergence with rate |g'(x*)| newton x_{n+1} = x_n - f(x_n) / f'(x_n) Quadratic convergence when f'(root) != 0 secant x_{n+1} = x_n - f(x_n) * (x_n - x_{n-1}) / (f(x_n) - f(x_{n-1})) Superlinear convergence: order ~1.618 (golden ratio) Bisection finds root within tolerance |f(bisect(f, a, b))| < tol when f(a)*f(b) < 0 Newton converges to root |f(newton(f, df, x0))| < tol when f'(x*) != 0 Bisection interval halving width_n == (b - a) / 2^n Secant method finds root |f(secant(f, x0, x1))| < tol Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 5 Solvers Burden & Faires (2015) Numerical Analysis, 10th Ed."},{"stem":"optimization-v1","path":"contracts/optimization-v1.yaml","description":"Numerical optimization — golden-section search, Newton's method for minimization, gradient descent. Covers the optimization chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["golden_section","gradient_descent","newton_optimize"],"obligation_types":["postcondition","postcondition","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Golden section finds minimizer","Newton optimization converges","Gradient descent monotone decrease","Golden section shrink rate"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 6 Optimization","Nocedal & Wright (2006) Numerical Optimization, 2nd Ed."],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"optimization-v1 Numerical optimization — golden-section search, Newton's method for minimization, gradient descent. Covers the optimization chapter of nlib.\n golden_section phi = (1 + sqrt(5)) / 2; rho = 2 - phi\nx1 = a + rho*(b - a); x2 = b - rho*(b - a)\nif f(x1) < f(x2): b = x2 else: a = x1\nrepeat until |b - a| < tolerance\n Interval shrinks by factor (2 - phi) ~ 0.618 each step gradient_descent x_{n+1} = x_n - alpha * grad_f(x_n) Linear convergence for strongly convex f Sufficient decrease: f(x_{n+1}) <= f(x_n) - c*alpha*|grad|^2 newton_optimize x_{n+1} = x_n - f'(x_n) / f''(x_n) Quadratic convergence near minimum Golden section finds minimizer |b - a| < tol at termination for unimodal f Newton optimization converges |f'(x*)| < tol when f''(x*) > 0 Gradient descent monotone decrease f(x_{n+1}) <= f(x_n) for appropriate alpha Golden section shrink rate interval ratio == (2 - phi) per step Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 6 Optimization Nocedal & Wright (2006) Numerical Optimization, 2nd Ed."},{"stem":"random-generators-v1","path":"contracts/random-generators-v1.yaml","description":"Pseudo-random number generators — Linear Congruential Generator, Mersenne Twister. Covers the PRNG chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["lcg","mersenne_twister"],"obligation_types":["bound","invariant","bound","invariant"],"properties":["LCG output range","LCG deterministic","MT output range","MT deterministic"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 9 Random Numbers","Knuth (1997) TAOCP Vol. 2 Seminumerical Algorithms, 3rd Ed.","Matsumoto & Nishimura (1998) Mersenne Twister: A 623-dimensionally equidistributed PRNG"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"random-generators-v1 Pseudo-random number generators — Linear Congruential Generator, Mersenne Twister. Covers the PRNG chapter of nlib.\n lcg x_{n+1} = (a * x_n + c) mod m Period divides m Full period iff: gcd(c, m)==1, a-1 divisible by all prime factors of m, a-1 divisible by 4 if m divisible by 4 mersenne_twister MT19937: w=32, n=624, m=397, r=31\nx_{k+n} = x_{k+m} XOR (upper(x_k) || lower(x_{k+1})) * A\nwhere A = matrix with bottom row 0x9908B0DF\nTempering: y = x XOR (x >> u); y = y XOR ((y << s) & b); ...\n Period = 2^19937 - 1 (Mersenne prime) 623-dimensionally equidistributed LCG output range 0 <= lcg_next(x, a, c, m) < m LCG deterministic lcg(seed, a, c, m, n) == lcg(seed, a, c, m, n) (same seed same sequence) MT output range 0 <= mt_next() < 2^32 MT deterministic mt(seed, n) == mt(seed, n) Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 9 Random Numbers Knuth (1997) TAOCP Vol. 2 Seminumerical Algorithms, 3rd Ed. Matsumoto & Nishimura (1998) Mersenne Twister: A 623-dimensionally equidistributed PRNG"},{"stem":"sorting-v1","path":"contracts/sorting-v1.yaml","description":"Sorting algorithms — quicksort, mergesort, heapsort. Covers the sorting and searching chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["heapsort","mergesort","quicksort"],"obligation_types":["postcondition","postcondition","postcondition","postcondition","invariant"],"properties":["Output is sorted","Output is a permutation of input","Mergesort stability","Heapsort sorted output","Permutation invariant (all sorts)"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 3 Sorting","Cormen et al. (2009) Introduction to Algorithms, 3rd Ed. — Part II Sorting"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":5,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"sorting-v1 Sorting algorithms — quicksort, mergesort, heapsort. Covers the sorting and searching chapter of nlib.\n heapsort heapsort(A):\n  build_max_heap(A)    // O(n)\n  for i in (1..len).rev():\n    swap(A[0], A[i])   // max to end\n    sift_down(A[..i], 0)  // restore heap\n Always O(n log n) time (no worst case degradation) In-place (O(1) auxiliary space) mergesort mergesort(A):\n  if len(A) <= 1: return A\n  mid = len(A) / 2\n  L = mergesort(A[..mid])\n  R = mergesort(A[mid..])\n  return merge(L, R)\nmerge: interleave L, R maintaining sorted order\n Always O(n log n) time Stable sort (equal elements preserve order) O(n) auxiliary space quicksort quicksort(A, lo, hi):\n  if lo < hi:\n    p = partition(A, lo, hi)  // Lomuto or Hoare\n    quicksort(A, lo, p - 1)\n    quicksort(A, p + 1, hi)\npartition: choose pivot, rearrange so A[<p] <= pivot <= A[>p]\n Average O(n log n), worst O(n^2) In-place (O(log n) stack space) Output is sorted forall i in 0..n-1: result[i] <= result[i+1] Output is a permutation of input multiset(output) == multiset(input) Mergesort stability equal elements preserve original relative order Heapsort sorted output forall i: result[i] <= result[i+1] Permutation invariant (all sorts) multiset(output) == multiset(input) for all three sorts Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 3 Sorting Cormen et al. (2009) Introduction to Algorithms, 3rd Ed. — Part II Sorting"},{"stem":"statistics-v1","path":"contracts/statistics-v1.yaml","description":"Descriptive and inferential statistics — mean, variance, covariance, correlation, chi-squared goodness-of-fit. Covers the statistics chapter of nlib.\n","equations":["chi_squared_fit","correlation","covariance","mean","variance"],"obligation_types":["bound","bound","postcondition","invariant","postcondition"],"properties":["Variance non-negative","Correlation bounded","Chi-squared non-negative","Covariance symmetry","Mean within data range"],"references":["Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 12 Statistics","Wasserman (2004) All of Statistics"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":5,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":3,"corpus_text":"statistics-v1 Descriptive and inferential statistics — mean, variance, covariance, correlation, chi-squared goodness-of-fit. Covers the statistics chapter of nlib.\n chi_squared_fit chi2 = sum_{i=1}^{k} (O_i - E_i)^2 / E_i chi2 == 0 when O == E Approximately chi-squared distributed with k-1 df under H0 correlation r = cov(x, y) / (std(x) * std(y)) correlation(x, x) == 1.0 correlation(x, -x) == -1.0 covariance cov(x,y) = (1/(n-1)) * sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - mu_x)(y_i - mu_y) cov(x, y) == cov(y, x) (symmetric) |cov(x,y)| <= std(x) * std(y) (Cauchy-Schwarz) mean mu = (1/n) * sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i mean([c; n]) == c for any constant c mean(x + k) == mean(x) + k (shift invariance) variance sigma^2 = (1/(n-1)) * sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - mu)^2  (Bessel correction) variance([c; n]) == 0 for any constant c variance(a*x + b) == a^2 * variance(x) Variance non-negative variance(x) >= 0.0 for all x with n > 1 Correlation bounded -1.0 <= correlation(x, y) <= 1.0 Chi-squared non-negative chi_squared(O, E) >= 0.0 Covariance symmetry cov(x, y) == cov(y, x) Mean within data range min(x) <= mean(x) <= max(x) Di Pierro (2023) Annotated Algorithms in Python, 3rd Ed. — Ch. 12 Statistics Wasserman (2004) All of Statistics"}],"score_cache":{"integration-v1":0.59375,"statistics-v1":0.56,"graph-algorithms-v1":0.6125,"optimization-v1":0.59375,"matrix-algebra-v1":0.59375,"nonlinear-solvers-v1":0.59375,"monte-carlo-v1":0.59375,"random-generators-v1":0.59375,"sorting-v1":0.575,"fourier-transform-v1":0.65},"pagerank_cache":{"statistics-v1":0.10000000000000007,"fourier-transform-v1":0.10000000000000007,"sorting-v1":0.10000000000000007,"graph-algorithms-v1":0.10000000000000007,"random-generators-v1":0.10000000000000007,"matrix-algebra-v1":0.10000000000000007,"nonlinear-solvers-v1":0.10000000000000007,"optimization-v1":0.10000000000000007,"integration-v1":0.10000000000000007,"monte-carlo-v1":0.10000000000000007}}